A number of countries in East Africa require the evidence of vaccination against yellow fever as a condition for granting entry to other East Africans.
But the issue gets more complex where the demand is for a citizen to be subjected to compulsory vaccination within the country of his nationality. As said before, some persons object to this on the ground that this constitutes an intrusion in to their private affairs that is health. In the United States, the main decision here is the Case of Jacobson against the State of Massachusetts.
This case arose after regulations passed in 1902 by the Board of Health of Cambridge, being of the opinion that it was necessary for the public health and safety, required the vaccination and revaccination of all the inhabitants of the state.
Anti-vax
This vaccination was compulsory but free. Pastor Jacobson refused to be vaccinated. He was charged with an offence, convicted and fined.
On appeal all the way to the Supreme Court, Jacobson argued that subjecting him to a fine or imprisonment for neglecting or refusing vaccination was an invasion of his liberty, the law was “unreasonable, arbitrary and oppressive”, and that one should not be subjected to the law if he or she objects to vaccination, no matter the reason.



