There is a paradox that although medical treatment is intended to improve the health and well-being of the patient, an adult and sane person may exercise the right to refuse medical treatment even though that refusal may seem unwise, foolish or ridiculous or may even be directly harmful to his health. This right is founded on the respect for the autonomy of the individual and the right to protect the integrity of his body. These rights are predicated on the fundamental rights of the individual in the constitutions of most states.
In Argentina for example, there is a law known as the Patient’s Rights Act, which permits a person do decline treatment. The Supreme Court has previously ruled on patients’ right to autonomy in a case in 1993 which dealt with a patients who needed blood transfusions but, declined to have it on account of religious objection. The patient was conscious when he refused the transfusion.



