The Supreme Court upheld the patient’s choice and said that patients, when accepting or refusing a specific treatment, “have the right to make a choice according to their own values or points of view, even when it may seem irrational or imprudent, and that free choice must be respected.”
In India, the Supreme Court in the case of K.S Puttaswamy v Union of India also known as the Ardhar Case, held that the right to privacy is not absolute and may be curtailed as long as the procedure is fair, just and reasonable and as long as the proportional restrictions further a legitimate state aim.
Public good
Therefore , on account of public health, order, morality the right to practice religion may be subordinated to the larger public objective to contain and prevent disease and that there is sufficient constitutional leeway for the government to claim the power to enforce compulsory vaccination.
In Kenya, these same arguments may apply although there is a right to healthcare and adequate healthcare services. Mandated as rights and not obligations, there is doubt whether this could be used to empower the state to mandate mass vaccination on all citizens.
However, the Public Health Act requires every parent to ensure that every child is vaccinated against small pox. It also states that a child may not be admitted to a school if such child has not been vaccinated or does not show evidence of vaccination.



